-- в”Ђв”Ђ Indico в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Open-source event management platform built at CERN for organizing conferences, meetings, and lectures with registration, papers, and room booking.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Self-Hosted$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2002, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Geneva, Switzerland$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Indico Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Indico is CERN's open-source event management platform for conferences and meetings. Explore its features, self-hosted pricing, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Indico is a free, open-source event management system originally developed at CERN, the European Organization for Nuclear Research, to organize meetings, lectures, workshops, and large conferences. Its roots trace to a European Union-funded project called the Integrated Digital Conferencing Project (InDiCo), launched in May 2002 as a two-year effort to build a flexible, catch-all platform for hosting meetings and conferences; when the EU project ended, CERN took over development based on the core modules already built (originally called MaKaC, or 'Make a Conference') and formally adopted the software as its own event-management solution in 2004, financing its development ever since. The first conference run entirely on the platform, CHEP 2004, is informally referred to within the project as 'event 0.' Indico is MIT-licensed and built primarily in Python using the Flask web framework on the backend, with SQLAlchemy managing access to a PostgreSQL database and a React-based front end for the modern web interface; the source code is maintained publicly on GitHub under the indico/indico repository. Functionally, Indico covers the full lifecycle of an event: creating and configuring conferences, meetings, and lectures with flexible timetables; managing registration and participant lists; multi-level access and security controls for restricting who can see or edit event content; document and material management for uploading and archiving presentations, slides, and papers; a peer-review workflow for conference paper submissions; and room and resource booking for physical meeting spaces. Because it was built to run CERN's own operations, Indico is proven at very large scale вЂ” CERN itself uses it to manage more than 900,000 events and over 200 meeting and conference rooms, and the United Nations has used Indico since 2016 to run conferences with more than 180,000 participants. Beyond CERN and the UN, Indico is installed at more than 300 organizations worldwide, including research institutes and universities such as the Max Planck Institute for Physics, and its ongoing development draws contributions from more than 100 developers, translators, and usability specialists across many countries, reflecting a genuinely global open-source community rather than a single vendor. There is no official SaaS or hosted-cloud edition sold by CERN; organizations self-host Indico on their own infrastructure, and pricing is effectively the cost of hosting and any optional professional services or support arrangements an institution chooses to procure. This makes Indico's primary audience research institutions, universities, scientific collaborations, standards bodies, and international organizations that need enterprise-grade conference and meeting management with full archival and access-control capabilities, but that prefer (or require, for data-sovereignty reasons) a self-hosted, source-available system over a commercial SaaS product. Its closest competitors in the conference-and-event-management space include commercial SaaS tools like Cvent, Eventbrite, and Whova, as well as academic-conference-specific systems like EasyChair and OpenConf; Indico differentiates itself by being fully open source and self-hosted, purpose-built for scientific and institutional event workflows (timetables, paper review, room booking, and long-term digital archival) rather than ticketing and marketing-oriented event promotion, and by having two decades of production hardening at one of the world's largest research organizations.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '367a6bce-9b7f-4b10-9faa-47430b894121';

